@node "Scores" "Scores, Rating & Standings"

@{b}->  SCORES and RATING@{ub}

The current rating system implies that points are awarded according to both
standing for each track and the amount of time that you are behind the time
that's above you and the time that leads for that circuit. The smaller the
difference in time, the smaller the difference in points awarded.

The maximum number of points to be gained (naturally by occupying 1st place)
is 20 points. No need to say that this person has the highest average speed.
From that spot on the remaining points are spread to 0 over the times that
follow, up until the point where (only) 95% of the highest average speed
is achieved. Lower average speeds receive 0 (zero!) points...
This means that there isn't a fixed number of people collecting points, but
that it depends upon the 'closeness' of the records for that track.
There's no way to get more rewards for your efforts ! ;)
  
Whenever a position changes, due to others attaining better laptimes or 
beating your own record,  scores for the previous position will be erased
and updated from scratch using the system explained above. In case you were
wondering why the total of each circuit score added together sometimes
doesn't quite match the overall below: it's a case of rounding. The scores
you see everywhere are rounded, but the total is calculated from a more
accurate number, only to be rounded at the very end.

Current standings are as follows. Positions based on the score and, when
equal scores exist, on a ratio that is calculated as average position
divided by the number of tracks that times were set on (quite unlikely)
Notice that you always get a point for having times, no matter what
they score.

